    {
      "id": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/lamb-courgette-and-orange-stir-fry",
      "url": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/lamb-courgette-and-orange-stir-fry",
      "title": "Lamb, courgette & orange stir-fry",
      "content_html": "<h1 style=\"text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;\">Lamb, courgette & orange stir-fry</h1>\n        <br>\n        <img src=\"https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/lamb-courgette-and-orange-stir-fry.webp\" style=\"text-align:center;\"/>\n        <br>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif;>This dish is light and, with the use of orange and its juice, is fresh-tasting with a touch of citrus sweetness. Traditionally, lamb stir-fries are served with broccoli or asparagus, but here I give it a modern make-over, using courgette instead. The secret to making a delicious stir-fry in minutes is to slice the lamb thinly. It takes less time to cook and the succulent texture is preserved.</p>",
      "image": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/lamb-courgette-and-orange-stir-fry.webp",
      "date_published": "2026-05-10T00:00:00+00:00Z",
      "language": "en"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/courgette-dill-and-lemon-farfalle",
      "url": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/courgette-dill-and-lemon-farfalle",
      "title": "Courgette, dill & lemon farfalle",
      "content_html": "<h1 style=\"text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;\">Courgette, dill & lemon farfalle</h1>\n        <br>\n        <img src=\"https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/courgette-dill-and-lemon-farfalle.webp\" style=\"text-align:center;\"/>\n        <br>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif;>A bright, late-summer dish that takes about 15 minutes from first chop to eating! The lemon slices cook down so the skin softens and the juice naturally disperses, leaving you with a really zingy pasta dish \u2013 try to slice the lemon as finely as you can to help the slices cook down in the time.</p>",
      "image": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/courgette-dill-and-lemon-farfalle.webp",
      "date_published": "2026-05-08T00:00:00+00:00Z",
      "language": "en"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/zinger-burgers",
      "url": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/zinger-burgers",
      "title": "Zinger burgers",
      "content_html": "<h1 style=\"text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;\">Zinger burgers</h1>\n        <br>\n        <img src=\"https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/zinger-burgers.webp\" style=\"text-align:center;\"/>\n        <br>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif;>You\u2019ll want to add the ingredients for these unbelievably crispy Zinger Burgers to your next shopping list! Piled high on wholemeal buns, with lettuce leaves and your choice of sauce (we\u2019d go for light mayo or homemade salsa), they\u2019re far lighter than you\u2019d expect at less than 400 calories each. Forget about breadcrumbs \u2013 we\u2019ve smashed together fiery tortilla chips, flour and a simple blend of store-cupboard spices instead. You can trust your air fryer to keep the chicken breasts nice and juicy, while the zingy coating bakes until it looks and tastes like it\u2019s been deep-fried at a restaurant.</p>",
      "image": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/zinger-burgers.webp",
      "date_published": "2026-05-03T00:00:00+00:00Z",
      "language": "en"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/chinese-bbq-pork-noodle-soup",
      "url": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/chinese-bbq-pork-noodle-soup",
      "title": "Chinese BBQ pork noodle soup",
      "content_html": "<h1 style=\"text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;\">Chinese BBQ pork noodle soup</h1>\n        <br>\n        <img src=\"https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/chinese-bbq-pork-noodle-soup.webp\" style=\"text-align:center;\"/>\n        <br>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif;>BBQ pork, known as Char Siu, is one of the most popular Guangdong dishes and goes well with rice or noodles. For a really tasty dish, marinate the pork well in advance so that the flavours penetrate the meat.</p>",
      "image": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/chinese-bbq-pork-noodle-soup.webp",
      "date_published": "2026-04-26T00:00:00+00:00Z",
      "language": "en"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/korean-beef-bulgogi-rice-bowls",
      "url": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/korean-beef-bulgogi-rice-bowls",
      "title": "Korean beef bulgogi rice bowls",
      "content_html": "<h1 style=\"text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;\">Korean beef bulgogi rice bowls</h1>\n        <br>\n        <img src=\"https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/korean-beef-bulgogi-rice-bowls.webp\" style=\"text-align:center;\"/>\n        <br>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif;>This has gone straight to the top of my favourite quick way to use beef mince! An easy version of Korean Beef Bulgogi, one of Korea's most famous food exports, made with ground beef rather than pricey steaks but using an authentic Bulgogi marinade so it takes a fraction of the effort and cost. I\u2019ve made rice bowls, there's many ways to serve this - noodles, rice wraps, burritos or tacos (so trendy!). See in post for list!PS Don't skip the apple and grated onion. This is what sets bulgogi apart from generic soy + sugar + garlic \"Asian\" sauces!</p>",
      "image": "https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/korean-beef-bulgogi-rice-bowls.webp",
      "date_published": "2026-04-25T00:00:00+00:00Z",
      "language": "en"
    },
